mics like Brzezinski soon replaced the old establishment figures who had mired the country in Vietnam, and they transformed the way America conducted foreign policy. Justin Vaïsse offers the first biography of the successful immigrant who completed a remarkable journey from his native Poland to the White House, interacting with influential world leaders from Gloria Steinem to Deng Xiaoping to John Paul II. This complex intellectual portrait reveals a man who weighed in on all major foreign policy debates since the 1950s, from his hawkish stance on the USSR to his advocacy for the Middle East peace process and his support for a U.S.-China global partnership. Through its examination of Brzezinski’s statesmanship and comprehensive vision, Zbigniew Brzezinski raises important questions about the respective roles of ideas and identity in foreign policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBrzezinski, Zbigniew,-1928-2017. 0aNational security-United States-History-20th century. 0aPolish Americans-Biography. 0aStatesmen-United States-Biography. 0aUnited States-Foreign relations-20th century. 0aUnited States-Strategic aspects. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674919501423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674919501.jpg  a978-3-11-060662-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles